Comment: R.I.P ASSASSIN'S CREED. The one who says that Odyssey was a good "ASSASSIN'S CREED" game or that it was the best has never played any ASSASSIN'S CREED game before origins. There probably won't even be a hidden blade or good stealth. ASSASSIN'S CREED has never been meant to be an RPG. It's main point was to show you the Assassin-Templar conflict. Does it even look like an ASSASSIN'S CREED game? Of course no. Where is the Assassin-Templar conflict? Where's the brotherhood? Where are the Assassins? The Templars and the Assassins have never existed before the Crusades. According to ASSASSIN'S CREED SYNDICATE, the conflict has ended with the Assassins victory after the industrial revolution. And the brotherhood didn't exist after that. Because there were no more Templars to fight. Despite the name, it's not a great RPG and nothing special about it. It's an RPG game that will be boring after you play it for 10 minutes.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: I'm on my 3rd playthrough, as this game is amazing. So much thought went into the little details too... My Kassandra was riding Phobos to a Spartan camp for a conquest battle, when a bear suddenly chased her into their encampment. I watched 8 Spartans in the camp kill the bear, but one of the Spartan soldiers died in the fight. The cool part came when one of the Spartans knelt down beside the dead body and said something akin to "I'll miss you brother". Something similar happened when I killed a wolf owned by a Beastmaster in a Huntress camp. The Beastmaster knelt down beside her dead wolf and told it "I'll never forget you..."  Definitely evokes pathos for some NPCs

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: Honestly, I saw this trailer and thought it'd be pretty cool. Then I remembered that it's an RPG. and that turned me off. I bought the game, beat it with the good endings. But honestly, there is no AC story here. The only time the word "assassin" is mentioned is when the MC says "wait, im not an assassin!" and when you're out of the animus for a whopping 30 minutes. There's no hidden blades. The freerunning is great, I love not being bound by a set path to accomplish the mission, this should've been the forefront of the feature from the very beginning. I'm halfway on the RPG aspect, I hate grinding for levels and for gear and weapons but I love decisions and shaping MY story. I feel like AC was always meant to the way it was, just exploring new timelines and stories with better mechanics and new features. The biggest turn off of this game is there is no Assassin Brotherhood. It's just the MC (you can count ONE of their ship's crew since you can call them in AS A DISTRACTION). Honestly they could've just removed "Assassin's Creed" and just called it Odyssey and it would've been an amazing game with an amazing story, but there's no link to the other AC games. Hopefully they realize the error of their ways.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: If you want to know the truth about what happened to "Assassin's Creed", read this please : During the development of AC Brotherhood, Ubisoft approached Patrice Desilets (the maker of AC and a worker at UBI since PoP 1) to demand yearly releases for AC since it was selling very well (10m copies AC1 - PoP 3m) Patrice, working in Gaming out of passion and not greed, refused. The result was that they fired him after 20 years of work.Every other AC that came after AC Brotherhood felt "different" or "lacking" something and that's SOUL, that's what it's lacking. Patrice went on to his own studio, working on a spiritual successor to AC called 1666: Amsterdam (there is a YT trailer) but guess what happened, UBI bought his studio and acquired the IP then fired Desilets. It was a threat to AC since it was made by the man who brought their cash cow to life. It took years of legal battle to get the assets back but now they are outdated and UBI has sunk its teeth too deep in AC's neck to change anything about it. AC 3, AC 4, ROGUE, UNITY etc, they're NOT CANON. They're either spin offs or shadows of the true AC. Before you say that it's just an opinion, the ORIGINAL author was fired. Imagine Game Of Thrones without George RR Martin. How would that be? Oh wait no need to imagine, just go watch the show post George's direction. It's being called bad fanfiction, that's what AC post Ezio is, FANFICTION. The original author was ousted, with him went Jasper Kyd, Jade Raymond and so on. Every other AC that came after Rev was an amateur chef trying to replicate the recipe as right possible. Yet they all miss the point, it's not about the profit or the rentability it's about the process, the passion, and that is gone with Desilets.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
Curious. Personally, my experience with the Assassin's Creed games began and ended with Revelations, a fantastic game in my opinion, but at the same time I have very little with which to set expectations beyond 'sneak up and murder people'.

Don't personally care much about whether the protagonist's male or female, not now they're delving into myth and giving a good excuse to sideline biological differences (Not being sarcastic), but with potentially interesting characters, an intriguing amount of appearances for armour and the promise of using the most underrated weapon in history, _spears,_ this looks quite promising.

And like that of the A.C. series, my experience with Ubisoft in general has been limited but favourable, so I have no pre-existing negative impressions of the company. Quite fond of For Honor.

:
This was my thought aswell. I read allmost only comments that defend the game like fans would do, but no real dislikes. The first ac game maked me happy of is unique way of gamestyle, stealth, freerunning and especially the fightscenes. Were you attack and counter at the wright time to orchestra a bloodbad of badguys laying on the ground around you. In timeperiods were the sword is ruling. Going true Brotherhood this was evolved. Now seeing the last versions of AC, seeing lifebars and hittingpoints hack&slash true eachother brings the realism and romans of the style it ones had. I hope someday thuis franchise will bring back the quality back instead of the quantity, at the whol game but allso in the detailed fights. Fightscenes with movie style combo's the makes your heart pump faster, not lifebars but limbs coming of or realistic cuts making your opponent weaker. Making it less arcade and keeping it true to the first intention. That means less games and more developing time. And if these changes means smaller maps to run the game so be it. A bigger map isn't always better if you only can run around to do nothing. I would have gladly compromise in these facts to get a better qaulity game in my opion. I hope AC will become what of once was and probably was ment to be.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
Ubisoft please listen to this:

I am playing AC Origins for the first time atm. Hated it at first, but then started loving it AFTER I turned out the HUD completely. The HUD ruins the gameplay for me. It makes the game feel too much like a checklist to go from marker to marker. Also it ruins the immersion. But there are still major irritating points:

- The game is not designed to play without a HUD. In old games finding your way from point to point was part of the game. You had your map with no markers, only names of towns and a few landmarks. Orientating yourself on the map, talking to people looking to roadsigns etc... made you find your way. As I play without a HUD, in some parts (after you kill the oracle in Sewu) you go hunting with your son. On one moment he wants to teach his son how to get rid of his fear, and to follow him to the top of the cliff. There are a lot of spaces that correspond to this description, no way to know where you need to be unless you toggle your HUD back on. This totally breaks immersion. 
- I can't configurate the HUD.¬† I like to keep some HUD elements, but if this is not within the presets I need to toggle the preset from full to¬†off constantly.

Please make AC (and all your open world games) in a way also people who want to play without a handholding checklist HUD can enjoy it to the fullest. If a world is crowded with people equipping every generic NPC with a few generic¬†lines like "follow this road, take the second right" or when driving a car make your direction lights go off or something like that. Make a kind of GPS system out of the people crowding the world.

Games who did it very good are for example Baldur's Gate 1 & 2, LA Noire (pressing 'x' made your partner say go straight)¬†and Shenmue (although on a much smaller scale). Deus ex mankind divide came close. You always had a description of where you needed to be, and by looking to streetnames, building numbers, room numbers,... you could find your way.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
People say they ruined the series with almost every entry, but those people are wrong. I've played every major assassin's creed and liked ALL of them for what they had. I had dissatisfaction but at no point EVER did they come close to ruining the series. I like that they are transforming the series unlike other developers who literally have used the same formula for decades. 

Origins was amazing and completely reinvigorated the series, though I felt Unity had amazing features that were overshadowed by negative opinions. The animations and parkour of Unity were by far the best of the series movement felt so solid, fluid and grounded. It also had co op, which was really nice but unfortunately shallow. I wish the open worlds had more to do in them aside from specific missions. Random events are nice, and the missions in origins were especially nice. You felt your legend growing there. I can only see them improving here.

I just want to spread a word of positivity among a whole barrage of negativity here..
The previous game, AC Origins, was one hell of game and pretty much exceeded my expectations with its incredible open-worldness, graphics and characters, (my fav being Reda, the Travelling orphan boy). I like the little snippets of information pertaining to Egyptian history and the game appearing on the loading screen. 
It's these little details that made me love AC Origins all the more. I'm truly excited for AC Odyssey, much love for the AC team for their work in the past and for future AC games ;)

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
God, i'm really mixed about this game...
Don't get me wrong; the game looks good and will probably be good. But as an Assassin's Creed game? Uhm...
I have some worries, but they could all be fixed by an narrative explanation or story focus.

First, no assassin's creed, it is weird. I know one of the major idea of an AC is to visit a place at a time period; but without the main focus of the creed, why still call it like this, apart from reputation sells. Let's make a spin-off serie then, named Animus Stories (for exemple). 
However, if the game storyline is really on the ancient civilization and their artefacts (i mean 65% of the story on them); then ok, it can be considered in the Assassin's Creed saga Story for me.

Second, the choices. The animus is supposed to be a machine used to view the past of humanity, the REAL past. Not what someone have written, or choose to tell future generations, the actual events that happened long ago. Giving the opportunities of choices leading to different endings is, for me, a betrayal of that principle. 
But again ,if the present storyline tells me that it is a new animus, more than ever made for entertainment; where people can litteraly play, not witness the past, then ok. But I don't see how it could tie up with the new Layla's story...

So, yeah, really some issues with the game as it is show yet. Only time and a full personal gamethrough will tell me if I considered this an Assassin's Creed game, or something that lost its lead.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
Best AC Games For Me With Their Most Common Quotes That I Remember :-
 
1.AC 2-Because of that epic story, theme songs, ezio , characters and beautiful locations and that epic dialogues and missions.

"It is a good life we lead brother,
Ahh ! The best , may it never change and may it never change us "

2.AC Origins - That epic gameplay and combat and storyline and epic locations.

‚ÄúAncient writings, From the Old Kingdom‚Äù

‚ÄúSleep? I never sleep. I just wait. In the shadows. And I will kill you all. Everyone who sniffed the air that day in Siwa!‚Äù

3.AC Revelation- because of that epic ending, theme song , Altair and Ezio , Beautiful Storyline

"Desmond? I heard your name once before Desmond, a long time ago. And now It lingers in my mind like an image from an old dream. I do not know where you are, or by what means you can hear me. But I know you are listening. (he leaves his weapons) I have lived my life as best I could, not knowing its purpose, but drawn forward like a moth to a distant moon. And here, at last, I discover a strange truth. That I am only a conduit for a message that eludes my understanding. Who are we, who have been so blessed to share our stories like this? To speak across centuries? Maybe you will answer all the questions I have asked. Maybe you will be the one to make all this suffering worth something in the end."

"To say that nothing is true, is to realize that the foundations of society are fragile, and that we must be the shepherds of our own civilization. To say that everything is permitted, is to understand that we are the architects of our actions, and that we must live with their consequences, whether glorious or tragic."

4.AC Black Flag - Because Of that epic sea battles , storyline , theme , characters and nice graphics..
Didn't liked that shitty tailing missions

"For years I've been rushing around, taking whatever I fancied, not giving a tinker's curse for those I hurt. Yet here I am... with riches and reputation, feeling no wiser than when I left home. Yet when I turn around, and look at the course I've run... there's not a man or woman that I love left standing beside me."

5.AC Brotherhood - epic story , characters, Rome , missions

"Leonardo: "I'm painting this beautiful young woman. I'm really starting to see a masterpiece in this."

Ezio : "Well, don't let beautiful women distract you from my weapon designs." Or something to that effect.

Leonardo: "Don't worry. You'll find that women aren't a distraction for me..." or something to that effect, but distraction was definitely in there.

Ezio: "Wait, I don't get it..."

6.AC Rogue - Templar experience , story, nothing else.

"Life's hardest choices are the ones that force you to question your own moral code"

7.AC 1 - Just because of my old memories with this game and Altair

"Men must be free to do what they believe. It is not our right to punish one for thinking what they do, no matter how much we disagree!"

8.AC 3 - didn't liked due to that very long intro , haytham sequences , open world and Connor too

"In your haste to save the world, boy, take care you don't destroy it."

But still it had a great modern day except that ending and had nice gameplay .

9.AC Syndicate - didn't liked it just because it was too modern and wasn't fit for an ac game.

"Escape plan? when no one's left walk out the front door."


BTW story was awesome and game had a nice gameplay with beautiful locations.

10.AC Unity -It wasn't that bad game except for the glitches and bugs . It had a great story and a decent main character (Arno) with absolutely beautiful Paris. But still it was the worst AC Ever

"The Creed of the Assassin Brotherhood teaches us that nothing is forbidden to us. Once, I thought that meant we were free to do as we would. To pursue our ideals, no matter the cost. I understand now. Not a grant of permission. The Creed is a warning. Ideals too easily give way to dogma. Dogma becomes fanaticism. No higher power sits in judgement of us. No supreme being watches to punish us for our sins. In the end, only we ourselves can guard against our obsessions. Only we can decide whether the road we walk carries too high a toll. We believe ourselves redeemers, avengers, saviours. We make war on those who oppose us, and they in turn make war on us. We dream of leaving our stamp upon the world... even as we give our lives in a conflict that will be recorded in no history book. All that we do, all that we are, begins and ends with ourselves."

Some other best quotes :-

"Nothing is true everything is permitted"

"When I was a young man, I had liberty, but I did not see it. I had time, but I did not know it. And I had love, but I did not feel it. Many decades would pass before I understood the meaning of all three. And now, the twilight of my life, this understanding has passed into contentment

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
Undoubtably AC Odyssey looks amazing, the game play is sounding like it‚Äôs going to be pretty cool, etc... but... this isn‚Äôt Assassins Creed! It‚Äôs a historical action / adventure RPG, with the AC label stuck on it! 

I‚Äôve always been a fan of the series, ever since getting the very first AC when I got my PS3, all those years ago... and one of the things I really enjoyed (and has kept me buying and following the series), was the whole ‚Äòbigger picture‚Äô storyline, both in the past and the modern day! What‚Äôs happened to that?! What‚Äôs happened to Juno, Minerva and the First Civilisation?! It seems like the whole Assassins / Templar / First Civilisation storyline, that formed the basis of AC, has just been totally scrapped before there was any definite end to it?!

In some ways, I feel a bit cheated that I‚Äôve religiously bought and played all way through each game, to see where the story was going... and now it‚Äôs like I‚Äôve now been told ‚ÄúYeah, forget everything that came before this, we can‚Äôt be bothered with that storyline anymore... so here something that looks great, but ‚Äòseemingly‚Äô has nothing to do with what AC is / was!‚Äù

I agree with a lot of people, that the franchise had been on a bit of a downward spiral, and was in need of a polish... and for me, AC Origins really brought it back ten fold, and to a point that was exactly what it said on the tin... the origins of the Assassins Creed! But now we‚Äôre going back before the ‚Äòorigins‚Äô?! I mean, ok.... closer to the First Civilisation I guess?!

All in all, although this looks amazing as a standalone game, I‚Äôm pretty apprehensive about the direction this now appears to be going storyline-wise! I hope I‚Äôm wrong, and I really hope that in some way this does feed into the ‚Äòcanon‚Äô storyline!

Comment:
Somebody help, I can either get this Assassin's Creed Odyssey or Ghost of Tsushima. What balances them as a worthy match are the graphics and the combat as far as I see. What gave GoTsu a boost was the fact it was by Sucker Punch Studios and they have made amazing InFamous games. What gave ACOdyssey a bring down was the fact you choose a path instead of reliving memories of ancestors. 

I understand that AC might of not made a game set in Asia to not to compete with GoTsu, I have read in the development of ACOrigins and it claims that a game set in Japan would have been a bad idea (same for Egypt and WW2) claims the creative director of AC4. Although the game set in Egypt was successful, they might of held back a start to a game in Japan. The era they would've chose to make an AC game in Japan was great too. Being set in Feudal Japan (1185-1603) with the samurais ect. overpowering the rich families who had power over the country.

The idea to a PROPER AC game set in Asia probably was never a plan since the last four years, they have been working on ACOrigins and ACOdyssey for 3-4 years since AC4. I really hope someday they have one set in Feudal Japan as it actually may be a beautiful nostalgic setting. 

I know little of GoTsu but if you can please answer my original question or support me with information I don't know. Thank you.

Comment:
Let me ask you all this: what makes an Assassin's creed game, an Assassin's creed game? It's in the title of the game! It's about (Assassin's) and about the (creed).
Here you play as a spartan? Right? If I'm wrong plz correct me! I'm just really confused? No Assassin's, no templars, no hidden blade, no Assassin's outfit with the hood and that stealth vibe to it. Yes this game look stunning and is prob really fun, BUT to call it an Assassin's creed game.... I don't know about that?

Yes I understand that this story take place before the creeds time, but plz let some of the lore be unknown and for us to piece together ourselfes. This is my opinion of what I'v seen so far. I know that like most things, change is necessary to keep games interesting but I just feel like this isn't it. The RPG style and lvl system is done in so many other games already. I was really enjoying the Assassin's games just because they didn't have that. And why is the so called hidden blade not a oneshot anmore? That's it's only  purpose.
Maybe I'm just to nostalgic. Let me know what u guys think!

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
They‚Äôve taken Assassin‚Äôs Creed... removed the assassin part... strayed from the roots... transformed the entire combat system into something totally different... and they‚Äôve effectively turned a stealth/assassination game into an action/hack-n-slash, level based RPG. Pretty sure it‚Äôs only called assassins creed because their milking the brand name for money because the brand name is massively popular. So this isn‚Äôt really assassins creed anymore. It should be called something else at this point, but they won‚Äôt do that because, well... because money.

It‚Äôs okay to change a series. Change is necessary... but only when done correctly. Changing it up in a franchise doesn‚Äôt mean turning the games into a totally different type of game. Completely transforming it into something it was never meant to be doesn‚Äôt work. Adding in enhancements and features, however, does work. We like the multiple approaches to each kill theory. That adds more variety and replayability to the game and makes it more fun. An example- look at AC2. It revamped the then-fledgling series with new mechanics and new features, while still retaining that core gameplay style from the first game. Look at brotherhood. It added the in-city horses, it added more weapon variety, it added in the ability to train and call assassins... all kinds of new stuff and refinements, while still retaining the features and gameplay of the older games. It didn‚Äôt change the games, it added to them and made them better. 

I‚Äôm still gonna buy this because it looks like a really awesome game as a whole, but I sure as hell won‚Äôt call it Assassin‚Äôs Creed. I‚Äôll come up with my own personal name for it.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
It absolutely seems like an Assassin's Creed game to me. Everything I want in an Assassin's Creed game is here: amazing historical setting, stealth, huge open world that I can explore freely climbing everything, cool combat, a new badass character to play as, a narrative filled with intrigue and interesting historical characters. Seriously, I don't understand how anybody can claim it doesn't seem like an Assassin's Creed game. 

Yes, it's evolving in some ways, adding a few more RPG like mechanics for example, but all longstanding series have to evolve to keep things from feeling stale.

How can anyone honestly think it isn't an Assassin's Creed game? Pointing to some small thing and saying "it isn't an Assassin's Creed game unless _____ is in it" is just subjective and arbitrary. It would be like me saying the new God of War game isn't a God of War game because it doesn't feature the blades of chaos or because it isn't doesn't have the mythological Greece setting or because they added a bunch of RPG elements.

Comment:
Im looking forward to playing it.  Odyssey is set during the time of the Greek Empire, which is about 500 or so years before Origins took place.  Origins took place almost half a century BC, after the Greek empire had become a thing of the past and the Roman Empire was about to take off hot and heavy.    The power of the Egyptian pharoahs was over by the time of Cleopatra and AC Origins.   It was a game set in a transitional period.   The cultures of Ancient Greece and Egypt still existed during Origins but were basically done for being of any significant importance.  Odyssey will show what that Ancient Greek culture was like when it was powerful and significant. Before there was ever an Alexandria or a Greek presence in Egypt.   
I don't care if it's about "assassins" or not.  It looks like a dope historical game

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: Completely feels like this is just an expansion pack add-on for Origins. It's Origins without the pyramids and sand dunes. I like the setting of ancient Greece, and I know ancient Egypt had some Greek influence on their culture, however I just don't like that the cities and areas in this look just like Origins. I can't tell the difference between the buildings or the people, all look the same as in Origins. The armor is slightly different but not much. Really can't tell it's a different game. That's what happens when you make games too quickly they took what two years off to make Origins and now they're right back for their yearly releases again. I thought after Origins they'd start putting more time and effort into their games, but evidently they just want to hurry up and cash in on the success of Origins. The games are usually really good quality for the amount of time put in, but they also usually feel just like the last game. It seems like they make an AC then a year later they come out with another AC that's very similar just with a slightly different setting. Origins was good and very different and much needed reboot for the series, that's because they took their time with it, this game they did not. They probably started on Odyssey right when they were finishing up Origins. Which is why they used many of the same templates. Which is why it looks very similar. If it wasn't for the absence of sand dunes and pyramids I would think they were still in Egypt... The map will also either be smaller, or just a copy and paste of Origins, no chance of it being bigger. I wouldn't be surprised if they copied and pasted the map and switched out the buildings and switched the sand for the ocean. I know I'm being very critical, but after Origins being the first AC I actually liked, I'm sure I'll enjoy this one too, I was just hoping for more after the beast that Origins was. And I certainly won't be pre-ordering this one like I did Origins. You might as well put this at $29.99 and call it an expansion and just have your character from Origins take a boat over to Greece. Because this game is pretty much just Origins 2.0, which is not a bad thing, just it should be it's own thing.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
I mean I like the idea of going back in time to see how the assassins came to be and I love the fact that we get to be spartans in this game but I feel like Assassins Creed isnt Assassins Creed anymore. Its just like any other typical hacknslash rpg now. They should of kept the Syndicate formula. The fast paced combat and instant kill assassinations made you feel like you were an assassin forreal. When you block you dont just block you counter kill by countering attacks at the right moment. When you attack you attack with array of fast paced attacks utilizing agility. When you successfully pulled off undetection you were rewarded with being able to take out one or more enemies with the iconic assassination moves. This combat formula is more ninjalike than what we got in Origins. I really dont see why they didnt stick with the Syndicate mechanics, it was the best we've seen up to that point. But I guess rpg elements have a way of seducing developers. I cant blame them I personally grew up playing hacknslash and rpgs alike. But still....Its just not Assassins Creed anymore. I rarely used stealth tactics in Origins. There was no need to unless it was a mission that required you to move undetected lest you fail the mission. Other than that I never really relyed on being an "assassin"....Damn shame...One of my favorite gaming series slowly losing my interest every new game that comes out... 

Honestly I kinda seen it coming with the death of Desmond. When I first played Assassins Creed, we slowly got to play with Desmond. Every new installement we got to play with Desmond more and more and there was no question the story was situated around him and his perspective on the assassins vs the templars in his timeline. Idk about everyone else but in the back of my heart I was hoping that every new installment we would eventually get to the point where we play as Desmond fully and completely with him fully recognized as an assassin in modern day time......Then he dies....And what? 3 er 4 games later and we STILL dont really know much about whats going on with the present day assassins and abstergo(present day templars) other than afew cutscenes and collectable items filled with lore candy?...Utterly dissapointed v.v

Comment: While I would have to agree that the franchise is taking a big deviation from its roots, this does look fun. But seriously people, just give the game a different title if you want to be creative. We are seeing so many games come out under already existing titles that on their own are fairly decent games, but when stuck with some big name fail to stand up to the standards their predecessors set. To throw out a possibly over used example (sorry :p) I like Dice‚Äôs battlefront 2 as a game. It‚Äôs solid. But because of its name, people keep expecting it to be some sort of remastered version of the 2005 battlefront 2. Because it didn‚Äôt live up to the expectations set by the first game (along with many questionable marketing choices) it gets flack. I just hope that even though this game has a clearly different tone from the norm of assassins creed, that we will still get a game that is fun to play.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: You're both an Assassin and a Greek. A Greek is a type of Person (Racially and Nationally), an Assassin is a Career choice. Also, Assassin's are'nt all Ninja's. They don't have to be stealthy, the point of an Assassin is to kill a target or target's and get away alive (Hopefully without being either Noticed, Recognized, or Trackable. Just need to have a Clean Escape and make sure no Witnesses could identify you out in the blue). Anyways, the point is, Assassin's can either be stealthy or not. It's only Loosing credibility for all of the people that don't like the fact it dives more into different parts of history, isn't completely stealth based, has wider free-roam aspects, and/or has customizable aspects (Such as weapons and outfits). In fact, it's been RPG-like for a while. It's not like stereotypical RPG, but it has always technically been an RPG. In all actuality, any game that has a story mode or quest aspect to it is an RPG. To be honest, it's just the fact it caters more to different people now. Like I said before, there are some aspects people don't quite like.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: I'm going to be perfectly honest.  I much prefer Origins than Odyssey from what I've seen. Odyssey looks awesome, fun, and improved on aspects that Origins started (it's weird how everyone but you has a shield though). And yet,  Origins had something that Odyssey lacks, a story connecting to the brotherhood. Odyssey is before assassins or templars were conceived and it lacks a connection. The story looks compelling, but this game should've been a new IP for Ubisoft. At this point, it's only AC to increase sales of the game. Despite how fun it looks, Origins isn't even 1 year old yet and there's still SO much to do. Still, the game looks great and I know a healthy amount of people will enjoy this title. :)

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
This may be the first time I'm impressed with an AC game since black flag five years ago. FINALLY some innovation to the series.

1: you can pick the gender of your protagonist. THANK YOU. Finally!!!!!!!!! How many times people have been saying that they want a female protagonist. This is not quite the same as a canon female-only protagonist, but hey, its a good start, and I'll gladly take it.

2: Full departure from the boring stale formula. No more templar vs assassin BS that is sooooooooooo overplayed overdone and overused in the past, we can finally see something a little different.

3: Branching storylines, with different endings based on your decisions, instead of a linear story. YES!!!!!!.

4: Full character customization.

For the first time, an assassin's creed game I am actually tempted to buy. I'm keeping my hype and expectations in check, because its been ages since I've played an ubisoft game I've actually enjoyed, but this one? this one looks like it has promise.

Comment: Honestly I'm getting real tired of all these people complaining about how assassins creed has taken a turn for the worse! I see people who havent even played origins complaining about it! If you didnt already know, when they made origins they completely redesigned  the game. You weren't some invincible pseudo god, you were a person. Who could be killed... a lot. If you at least play origins and get an understanding of where they're taking this franchise, then you'll realize that this game is going to be awesome! (And that Greece is the most sensible place to put a game because of origins.) In a word, I love where ubisoft has taken this franchise and as a assassins creed veteran, I can whole heartedly say that this game will be better then all of the ones before and you have no need to worry about anything like the sneaking aspect being taken out of the game.

Socrates, your mentor, is known as "the father of western philosophy"... aka "the father of understanding".  He guides you (as you saw in the demo at E3).  Alexios/Kassandra will become the Grand Master of the Templar Order. 

Origins was the Birth of the Creed.  Odyssey is the Birth of the Order.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
I have NO love of the movies version of Spartans in their leather speedos and helmets but something I think did go over well and needs to be in AC odyssey (for my spartan needs) are capes. Give me a nice long flowing red spartan cape please. It doesn‚Äôt need to block the character model or take up exorbitant space either. Just something profile fitting. Add it as a later advancement upon reaching higher levels too. I really think it would go well especially with the land battles and the over all leader of your troops feel. You could even make its visuals toggle so if players don‚Äôt want to add it then no harm no foul but it‚Äôs their for those of us that do want it. 

I totally can see the reasoning behind dual wielding but in a relatively historical game not having a shield is just absolutely inaccurate to the time. Shield bashing was a main-stay of combat back then and really was introduced by the Spartans as a way to effectively push enemies off the shield wall. Allow our characters to use shields please. Again, make its visuals toggle as to not affect the character model and what not but that is really something that needs to be in the game. 

Allow us to reforge The spear of Leonidas. This slightly dovetails into the shield argument but there is definitely a need to join your men in the shield wall with your spear and shield and hold the line shield bashing and then thrusting. Historically accurate and full of real time badass moments. Also reforging the spear (even if it‚Äôs in a later dlc) would still maintain the dual wielding integrity. Those Spears weren‚Äôt 12 feet long but rather only 7 to 8 feet. It could have easily been used in one had as a blunt trama weapon up close (similar to a quarter staff) to open up for a sword finish as-well as ranged thrusting and backward jabbing. You could really open the combat system up by allowing the reforged spear as a sidearm or main hand. Each hand would use it differently (additionally with the shield option aswell). 

With the prevalence of land battles I think it‚Äôs secretly everyone‚Äôs dream to have a battle similar to the scene from the movie Troy where Achilles and his men take the temple. As I‚Äôm sure that does not seamlessly fit into the game as is what about this being a challenge mode or even a multiple player mode. Player vs player attacker and defender. The seamless sea to land could really open up some great moments where a player could jump from the ship to the shore watching some of his men get raked by arrow fire building the intensity. 

The culmination of points 2,3,and 4 could be a commander option for the player. Assassins creed is already a control heavy game but what if there was an option for players to command their crew to form a shield wall or a wedge during those battle sequences. If not in a random battle they take part in through the story what about the ability to really command their crew of 50 or so men in a challenge battle. An option wheel could be used to issue commands like ‚Äúform wall, interlock shields, overhead cover, form wedge, advance in wedge, advance in wall, break formation.‚Äù  This might not work in the base story game but maybe a multiplayer beach attack could make use of this. Players could use the commands to fight with their crews really bringing the full force of their crew to bear. Imaging the attacking player forming a close shield wall and advancing but the defending player weakens it with archers then forms a wedge to punch through. 

Dovetailing onto 5 would be the topic of allowing players to tailor their crews with a standard uniform and weapon load out. Having a custom shield and insignia and color with armor options and helmet options would add variety. Giving your soldiers spears and shields or swords and shields would mix up how they fought. Using gold to buy the equipment and upgrade your crew to really have an small force at your disposal sort of working like a ‚Äúbrotherhood‚Äù you could call or opt to ‚Äúuse crew‚Äù if you wanted to feel like it wasn‚Äôt just you out there. This option could be limited to a multiplayer/challenge mode or could really be cool in the single player story to have an actually force to fight with and use with the formations. If the 150v150 ability is there for the game why not use it and add crews and everything about them to the game. You could even have time restricted ‚Äútraining times‚Äù where your crew isn‚Äôt available for combat for several hours as you train and outfit them as their level increases.

I have to say Ubisoft, I am thoroughly disappointed. The fact that you think we are gullible enough to believe that this is an AC game, is beyond me. Fair enough, release Odyssey, release Origins, but DO NOT try to crack that these are Assassins Creed games, because they are not. The historical settings, unbelievable storylines, and amazing characters, made the franchise unique. But what really made the franchise unique was the actual Assassins Creed part of the games, and ultimately, the past few games have let me down. 

The AC franchise holds a special place in my heart, as it was the first set of games I properly played, and allowed me to find a love and passion for gaming. It‚Äôs so sad to see the franchise go down this route such as the new conventional af combat system, barely any fucking parkour and a CONTROLLABLE EAGLE?! And the franchise will be truly missed. 

Call this comment gay all you want, but I needed to vent. 

R.I.P Assassins Creed.

Comment:
the game looks good, heck the story so far looks good too,  but I'm afraid to say this isn't Assassins creed anymore. It doesn't look like stealth is a strong focus in this game anymore and has a heavy focus on brutal combat (they did, however, improve combat a bit, especially the dodge animation from origins). this a prequel to Origins, which is way before the assassin order(hidden ones) was formed! that means no hidden blade (or at least they might show a beta hidden blade), no assassin robes, no creed, no emphasis on stealth,  so even story-wise and in terms of game mechanics, this isn't an assassins creed story.  

sorry Ubi, this is a pass for me. If anything this is good looking spinoff game. I'll come back to Assassins creed when the series has anything to do with assassination and stealth, cause right now all I see in Origins and Odyssey is a game about a skilled brutal warrior/hunter, not an efficient, stealthy, and skilled assassin.

Ok to clarify for people this is an Assassin‚Äôs Creed game. It may not look like it but it takes place in the same universe and deals with the First Civilization. Origins was the story of the brotherhood forming and this is a a journey for your character.

Why no social stealth of hidden blade? Because they did not do those yet. It will return most likely. This will continue the story and it is nice to see different things for the franchise even if this is coming from a fan since the beginning.

A lot more to say but will end it here. I am prepared to be downvoted as angry fans and players will not like my opinion. I would like to say that i am not big on some of the directions but I will get it to continue the story and have fun because that is the reason I play.

I was worried that they screwed up the gameplay, messed up the combat, and distanced the story too much from the Brotherhood. The actual product, however, was fantastic. It was refreshing, massive, and captivating and honestly one of the AC games imo. Odessey looks like they're borrowing a lot from Origins which could be boring if done improperly or very good if correctly done. All I'm saying is after they surprised me with Origins, I am more than willing to give Ubisoft the chance to surprise me again here.

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: Tbh I can see why some people are saying it's not even an AC game. Someone mentioned this game takes years and years and years before AC:Origins. So let's look back at what we know. We know that there were some proto-Assassins about (ex: Darius the Persian). Thanks to Origins we also know that the Templars, also had a proto group that goes back to around the 12th century BC. Someone also pointed out that Hippocrates was shown in this trailer. He was born in the 4th century BC. So we are fast forwarding by about 700 years give or take 50 years. So why reconstruct the timeline? The answer is that in the 4th century BC is when Alexander the Great was born roughly 30 years after Hippocrates was dead. It may seem like I'm shoehorning Alexander in and honestly I kind am. How can we have both Hippocrates and a peak Alexander at the same time? If we say the protagonist was born in the year 390 BC (Hippocrates died in 370) that would put us at 20 years of age. Alexander wasn't born until 356 BC.  We would be off by 26 years plus the time for him to have reached his peak form which adds roughly another 20 years. For those keeping track we're off by almost half a century. However, it's apparent to me that this game will give us a huge amount of lore with the pieces of Eden. The Templars and their precursor were obsessed with them and would hoard them and attempt to learn about them. Alexander the Great, in the lore, was supported by the Order of the Ancients and was given access to a piece of Eden. This game will probably revolve us around securing and learning about the Pieces of Eden. This game isn't about an Assassin, but an agent of the Order of the Ancients. We know that the order grew out of Egypt and expanded into Italy and possibly even the wider Mediterranean world. This game we will watch the main character grow to the lead the Greek order and eventually support Alexander the Great. Yes, the character will be almost 70, but keep in mind the character has "the blood of Leonidas", who lived to the ripe old age of around 60. So let's take off 20 years and say the main character comes into contact with Alexander's father and he reveals to him the secrets that we know. Historians know that Phillip, Alexander's father, had plans for a unified Greece and an invasion planned for the Persians. Obviously this didn't happen and Alexander was the one to achieve that. We also know that Alexander eventually did conquer Egypt, Persia and the rest of the near east. Alexander would be poisoned by a proto-Assassin and led to the cutting up of his empire. However I'm getting ahead of myself. Where's the proof? Well, in the trailer we hear them say something along the lines of "How can a child save us all if he's sentenced to death?" Why does this matter? It matters because this child, the main character, has a hand in creating one of the world's largest empires. By most standards, Alexander had a good empire. He stabilized Greece and made it a huge center of culture and placed it among one of the better places to live in. That's my theory and thank you for reading this wall of text

Title: Assassin's Creed Odyssey: E3 2018 Official World Premiere Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: I was really looking forward to seeing what they came up with this year. Unfortunately, I was left hella disappointed. It hasn't been even a year since they launched ACO and man, this looks so rushed! It looks like they milked out the colour scheme and graphics design completely off the previous game, just changed titles. I won't even dive into the newly introduced choices of freedom around the dialogue and how that will affect the whole animus' concept. If I were to base my arguments off of what I saw in the trailer,  nothing really gave off the idea it had anything to do with the assassins, except the title. At least not from what we are used to. I know it's physically impossible to put the whole concept into 2 min long trailer, but some of the most iconic elements were missing. No hidden blades in sight, no hay stacks nor the assassin's signature- the famous leap of faith. I really hope they continue to work on the Odyssey before its release date, but as someone who's been following the franchise's development for years, I might have to skip this one.

There's just one problem:
Ubisoft has stretched the A.C. brand label thin, in an effort to carry-over fans, and it shows. These games should be individual adventures to a historical episodic series, not canon sequels to a series once guided by an overarching storyline.

Judging by the comments, it seems like many of Ubisoft's fans and players agree with this sentiment.
